            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How council tax is calculated</h2>
              <p>
                Council tax is a local tax on residential properties in Great
                Britain. Each property is placed in a valuation band, and your
                local authority sets a yearly charge for a Band D property.
                Other bands are calculated as fixed fractions of Band D.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Step 1 – Band charge</p>
                <p>
                  <code>Band charge = Band D charge × band multiplier</code>
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">
                  Step 2 – Apply discounts and premiums
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Net charge = Band charge × (1 − total discounts +
                    premiums)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">
                  Step 3 – Convert to monthly / weekly
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code>Monthly ≈ Net charge ÷ 12</code><br />
                  <code>Weekly ≈ Net charge ÷ 52</code>
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Standard band multipliers</h3>
              <p>The statutory multipliers relative to Band D are:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>England &amp; Scotland (Bands A–H):</strong> A 6/9, B
                  7/9, C 8/9, D 9/9, E 11/9, F 13/9, G 15/9, H 18/9.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Wales (Bands A–I):</strong> A 6/9, B 7/9, C 8/9, D
                  9/9, E 11/9, F 13/9, G 15/9, H 18/9, I 21/9.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Northern Ireland does not use council tax bands; instead it has
                a domestic rating system based on property value and a regional
                rate. This calculator approximates NI bills by treating the
                entered figure as a Band D–equivalent charge.
              </p>

              <h2>Common discounts and exemptions</h2>
              <p>Key reductions the calculator can model include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Single person discount (25%)</strong> – if only one
                  adult is counted as living in the property.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Student exemption (100%)</strong> – if all residents
                  are full-time students.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Severe mental impairment exemption</strong> – if all
                  chargeable adults are severely mentally impaired and meet
                  benefit criteria.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Disability band reduction</strong> – if your home has
                  been adapted for a disabled person, the bill may be reduced by
                  one band.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Council Tax Reduction / Support</strong> –
                  income-based help with your bill, set by each council.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Empty / second home discounts or premiums</strong> –
                  some councils offer discounts for second homes or charge
                  premiums on long‑term empty properties.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                The exact rules and percentages vary by local authority. This
                tool uses typical values to give a quick estimate; always
                confirm with your council.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and data sources</h2>
              <p>
                Official council tax information, including banding and local
                charges, is published by:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <a
                    href="https://www.gov.uk/council-tax"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener"
                    >GOV.UK – Council Tax overview</a
                  >
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your local council’s website (for example Birmingham,
                  Edinburgh, Cornwall, Buckinghamshire)
                </li>
                <li>Citizens Advice and other independent guidance sites</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator does not pull live data from councils. For
                precise figures, refer to your latest bill or your council’s
                online council tax pages.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is council tax the same across the UK?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Each local authority sets its own Band D charge and may add
                parish, police and fire precepts. Bands and valuation dates also
                differ between England, Scotland and Wales, and Northern Ireland
                uses a separate domestic rating system.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I spread my council tax payments?</h3>
              <p>
                Most councils allow you to pay over 10 or 12 monthly instalments
                by Direct Debit. Some offer weekly or fortnightly options. The
                total yearly amount is the same; only the schedule changes.
              </p>

              <h3>What happens if I don’t pay?</h3>
              <p>
                Councils can issue reminders, court summons and liability
                orders, and may use enforcement agents (bailiffs), deductions
                from earnings or benefits, or in extreme cases, apply for
                committal to prison. If you are struggling, contact your council
                early to agree a payment plan or apply for Council Tax
                Reduction.
              </p>
